I live in the [ORG] dorm , room ###. I am emailing you because I am concerned for my safety here. [DATE], around #:## [ACRONYM] my roommate and I were up talking with the lights off while laying in bed. While I was laying in bed, I looked out of the window and saw a bright light flashing on and off. At first, I thought it was my roommates phone, but when I asked her to turn it off, the light was still there. After that, I told her that I thought there was someone outside of our window, because it was the only thing that made sense, since our window is facing the [ORG] building and there lights were off. I proceeded to look outside the window, but didn't see anything because it was too dark. After I looked outside the window, my roommate looked, and she did indeed see someone sitting right below our window. She said she saw someone with a phone and something else shiny and circular in his hands. My roommate tried to take a picture, but suspected that the guy thought we saw him, so he turned off his phone screen. When she looked again, she said he saw her, smiled, and then waved at her. We were immediately concerned and told our [ORG]. After we told her we came back into our room, and my roommate looked outside the window again and said he was gone. After, we told one of our friends and asked him to check it out, to see if the guy was still there. He went out side, while we were at the exit door watching and recording him. Our friend, found that a man was still under our window. He said that after he called out to see if anyone was there a second time, the man came out and said he was there. The man said he was just sitting there smoking because he didn't want to go anywhere else and be caught. Unfortunately my friend does not have great eyesight and was not wearing his glasses to see if he was actually smoking. Our friend was coming back in to tell us what happened, but I asked him to go back and tell the man to move from under our window and go to a different spot. My friend said that the man also said that he lived on the third floor of this side of [ORG]. I don't believe this to be true because, after my friend came back inside, my roommate, our friend, our friend's roommate, and I were sitting in the hallway on the first floor, talking about the situation, tay, tay's roommate and I saw him pass the exit door, about ##-## minutes later. This means that he waited ##-## minutes later to move from the spot he was in, after my friend asked him to leave. Also, [DATE] after that the man did not walk in to this side of [ORG], because my friends and I would of saw him, since we were in the hallway of the first floor. This also means that he was lying about where he lives. After my roommate and I finish talking in the hallway with our friends, we went into our room, locked the door, locked our window, and out a sheet over our blinds. My roommate and I were talking in our room and, she said that it looked like the man was a young white male, around our age. She got the best look at him. Even though we covered the blinds and locked our window, I still don't feel safe in my room at night after the situation. One reason is because, now I feel that I can't sleep with the window open, or even have it open for long periods of time, while I am by myself in the room, from fear that someone will cut through the screen and come in. Another reason is because the sheet that we have up, only covers about ##% of the window. My bed is against the window and a small portion isn't covered by the sheet, so now sometimes I feel that anyone can come to our window and look through the areas that are not covered. My last reason is that now I am almost afraid to look out of the window, from fear that someone might be looking back at me, or when I do, I still feel that someone might still be there, because I didn't even see the man outside my roommates and my window [DATE] morning. Unfortunately, I don't feel secure in my own room. It takes me a bit longer to fall asleep, which leaves me tired during [DATE], and I feel paranoid, when I am alone, compared to the times before this situation, were I felt safe, and I could fall asleep with no problem, or even stay up, purely because I want/need to, and not out. of paranoia or fear. I know [DATE] have passed, and my roommate and I haven't reported it, but that was because I was trying to "be brave", but after talking with my parents, I see that I can still "be brave", while also being cautious and safe. So I am emailing you this becauseI don't know what else to do or if anything can be done, but I wanted you to know about the situation. Thank you for taking the time to read this.
